{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17617010","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17617010"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:09:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:09:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16449"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16449","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16449"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.13,0.54,0.08,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9140"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75113"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9140","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9140"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16449"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60621"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1909"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7184"},{"type":"tags","id":"10317"},{"type":"tags","id":"10334"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21711"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21714"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75113","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75113"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EPseudobulbar palsy and true bulbar palsy are two distinct neurological conditions affecting speech and swallowing. They can be distinguished by careful examination of the cranial nerves.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most characteristic of pseudobulbar palsy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Tongue atrophy","Absent gag reflex","Spastic dysarthria","Fasciculations","Decreased jaw jerk"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPseudobulbar palsy results from bilateral upper motor neuron lesions affecting the corticobulbar tracts. \u003Cstrong\u003ESpastic dysarthria\u003C/strong\u003E is a characteristic feature, where speech is strained, slow and has a harsh quality due to spasticity of the bulbar muscles. This differs from the flaccid dysarthria seen in true bulbar palsy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect features are typically seen in true bulbar palsy:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETongue atrophy\u003C/strong\u003E occurs with lower motor neuron lesions. In pseudobulbar palsy, the tongue appears normal in bulk but movements are slow and spastic\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbsent gag reflex\u003C/strong\u003E suggests lower motor neuron involvement. In pseudobulbar palsy, the gag reflex is preserved or hyperactive due to loss of upper motor neuron inhibition\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFasciculations\u003C/strong\u003E are seen with lower motor neuron disorders, not in pseudobulbar palsy\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased jaw jerk\u003C/strong\u003E occurs with lower motor neuron lesions. In pseudobulbar palsy, the jaw jerk is typically brisk\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECommon causes of pseudobulbar palsy include stroke, multiple sclerosis, and motor neurone disease. The presence of emotional lability (pseudobulbar affect) helps distinguish it from true bulbar palsy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Pseudobulbar palsy presents with upper motor neuron signs including spastic dysarthria, emotional lability, and preserved gag reflex.","Bilateral upper motor neuron lesions affecting corticobulbar tracts cause pseudobulbar palsy.","True bulbar palsy differs from pseudobulbar palsy by showing lower motor neuron signs including tongue atrophy and absent gag reflex."],"references":["Ahmed A, Simmons Z. Pseudobulbar affect: prevalence and management. Ther Clin Risk Manag. 2013;9:483-9. doi: 10.2147/TCRM.S53906. Epub 2013 Nov 29. PMID: 24348042; PMCID: PMC3849173.","King RR, Reiss JP. The epidemiology and pathophysiology of pseudobulbar affect and its association with neurodegeneration. Degener Neurol Neuromuscul Dis. 2013 May 27;3:23-31. doi: 10.2147/DNND.S34160. PMID: 30890891; PMCID: PMC6065587.","Schiffer R, Pope LE. Review of pseudobulbar affect including a novel and potential therapy. J Neuropsychiatry Clin Neurosci. 2005 Fall;17(4):447-54. doi: 10.1176/jnp.17.4.447. PMID: 16387982.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60621"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16449"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60621","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60621"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-28T22:49:55+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-28T22:50:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9140"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75113"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.co